{"id":1,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Who discovered the magnetic effect of electric current?","answer":"Hans Christian Oersted discovered the magnetic effect of electric current in 1820.","keywords":["Hans Christian Oersted","discovered","1820"],"explanation":"The discovery that electricity and magnetism are linked was made by Hans Christian Oersted. This is discussed on page 48 of the textbook PDF.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":2,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":10,"max":20},"question":"What is a magnetic field?","answer":"A magnetic field is the region around a magnet or a current-carrying conductor where magnetic force can be felt.","keywords":["region around","magnetic force","felt"],"explanation":"The textbook defines the magnetic field as the area where the magnetic effect of current or a magnet is experienced. Found on page 48.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":3,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Which device is used to detect the presence of a magnetic field in a circuit?","answer":"A magnetic compass is used to detect the presence of a magnetic field.","keywords":["magnetic compass","detect","presence"],"explanation":"A magnetic compass needle deflects when brought near a magnetic field, making it a useful detector. Found in Chapter Notes page 3.","page_number":"3"},
{"id":4,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":20},"question":"What happens to the magnetic field when the electric current is switched off?","answer":"The magnetic field disappears the exact moment the electric current stops flowing.","keywords":["disappears","current stops","switched off"],"explanation":"Electromagnetism is temporary; it ceases to exist when the current is removed. Detailed on Slide 2 and textbook page 48.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":5,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Define an electromagnet.","answer":"A current-carrying coil of wire that behaves as a magnet is called an electromagnet.","keywords":["current-carrying coil","behaves","magnet"],"explanation":"An electromagnet is defined as a temporary magnet made by coiling wire around a core. Found on page 50 of the textbook.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":6,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Name a material commonly used as the core of an electromagnet.","answer":"Soft iron is commonly used as the core of an electromagnet.","keywords":["Soft iron","core","electromagnet"],"explanation":"Inserting an iron nail or soft iron core drastically magnifies the magnetic field's strength. Found on page 50.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":7,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"State one practical application of a lifting electromagnet.","answer":"Lifting electromagnets are used in scrapyards to lift heavy iron and steel objects.","keywords":["scrapyards","lift","iron objects"],"explanation":"Scrapyards and factories use lifting electromagnets attached to cranes. Found on page 52.","page_number":"52"},
{"id":8,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":10,"max":20},"question":"What is the heating effect of electric current?","answer":"The warming of a conductor when an electric current passes through it is known as the heating effect.","keywords":["warming","conductor","current passes"],"explanation":"When current faces resistance in a wire, it generates heat energy. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":9,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Which wire is preferred for making the heating element in electric appliances?","answer":"Nichrome wire is preferred for making heating elements in electric appliances.","keywords":["Nichrome wire","preferred","heating elements"],"explanation":"Nichrome offers higher resistance, producing more heat than ordinary copper wire. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":10,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Name two household appliances that work on the heating effect of electric current.","answer":"Electric room heaters and electric irons work on the heating effect of electric current.","keywords":["Electric room heaters","electric irons","heating effect"],"explanation":"These appliances intentionally use high-resistance wire to generate heat. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":11,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"What is a cell or battery?","answer":"A cell or battery is a device that generates electric current through internal chemical reactions.","keywords":["generates electric current","chemical reactions"],"explanation":"Cells convert chemical energy into electrical energy. Found on page 58 (Snapshots).","page_number":"58"},
{"id":12,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Who invented the first battery?","answer":"The first battery (Voltaic cell) was invented by Alessandro Volta.","keywords":["first battery","Alessandro Volta"],"explanation":"Volta proved that a combination of metals and liquid generated current. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":13,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"What are the two metal rods in a Voltaic cell called?","answer":"The metal rods in a Voltaic cell are called electrodes.","keywords":["metal rods","electrodes"],"explanation":"The electrodes are usually made of zinc and copper. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":14,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"What state is the electrolyte in a dry cell?","answer":"In a dry cell, the electrolyte is in the form of a thick moist paste.","keywords":["electrolyte","thick moist paste"],"explanation":"Unlike voltaic cells which use liquid, dry cells use a paste, making them portable. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":15,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"Which terminal does the zinc container represent in a dry cell?","answer":"The zinc container acts as the negative terminal in a dry cell.","keywords":["zinc container","negative terminal"],"explanation":"In a standard dry cell, the outer zinc casing is the negative electrode. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":16,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"very_short_answer","marks":1,"expected_word_count":{"min":5,"max":15},"question":"What is the primary advantage of a rechargeable battery?","answer":"Rechargeable batteries can be charged and reused multiple times, preventing waste.","keywords":["charged","reused multiple times"],"explanation":"This reduces e-waste and saves money over time. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":17,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"Why does a compass needle deflect when placed near a current-carrying wire?","answer":"The electric current flowing through the wire produces a magnetic field around it. This magnetic field interacts with the tiny magnet of the compass needle, causing it to deflect.","keywords":["produces magnetic field","interacts","tiny magnet","deflect"],"explanation":"Current creates a magnetic field, which applies force on the compass. Found on page 48.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":18,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":35},"question":"Why does a compass needle return to its original position when the current is switched OFF?","answer":"When the current is switched OFF, the magnetic field around the wire disappears. Without the magnetic force, the compass needle naturally aligns back to the Earth's magnetic north-south direction.","keywords":["magnetic field disappears","without force","aligns back","Earth's magnetic direction"],"explanation":"The magnetic effect is temporary and depends strictly on the flow of current. Found on page 48.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":19,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"Why are electromagnets considered temporary magnets?","answer":"Electromagnets only exhibit magnetic properties as long as electric current flows through their coil. Once the current stops, they immediately lose their magnetism.","keywords":["exhibit magnetic properties","current flows","lose magnetism","current stops"],"explanation":"They do not retain magnetism permanently. Found on page 50.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":20,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"What happens if you insert an iron nail into a current-carrying cylindrical coil?","answer":"Inserting an iron nail into the core of the coil drastically magnifies the magnetic field's strength, making the electromagnet much stronger.","keywords":["iron nail","core","magnifies","magnetic field strength"],"explanation":"The iron core concentrates the magnetic lines, enhancing the pull. Found on page 50.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":21,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"State two factors that affect the strength of an electromagnet.","answer":"The strength of an electromagnet can be increased by increasing the number of turns in the coil and by increasing the amount of electric current flowing through it.","keywords":["number of turns","increasing current"],"explanation":"More turns and more current mean a stronger magnetic field. Found on page 51.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":22,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":35},"question":"Why do heating appliances use nichrome wire instead of copper wire?","answer":"Nichrome offers much higher electrical resistance than copper. This higher resistance causes more electrical energy to be converted into heat, making it ideal for intentionally generating heat.","keywords":["higher electrical resistance","converted into heat","ideal"],"explanation":"High resistance is necessary for the heating effect to be prominent. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":23,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"What causes a wire to heat up when electric current passes through it?","answer":"When electric current flows through a conductor, it faces opposition known as resistance. This resistance converts some of the electrical energy into heat energy, warming the wire.","keywords":["faces opposition","resistance","electrical energy","heat energy"],"explanation":"Electrical friction (resistance) generates heat. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":24,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"easy","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":30},"question":"What is an electrolyte in the context of a Voltaic cell?","answer":"An electrolyte is a liquid, usually a weak acid or salt solution, that allows the flow of electric charges during the chemical reaction inside the cell.","keywords":["liquid","weak acid","salt solution","flow of charges"],"explanation":"It facilitates the chemical reaction between the electrodes. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":25,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"How can you reverse the poles of an electromagnet?","answer":"The poles of an electromagnet can be reversed by simply changing the direction of the electric current flowing through the coil, which is done by reversing the battery terminals.","keywords":["poles reversed","changing direction","electric current","reversing terminals"],"explanation":"Magnetic polarity is dependent on current direction. Found on page 51.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":26,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"Why does a Voltaic cell eventually stop working and become 'dead'?","answer":"Over time, the chemicals and electrodes involved in the reaction inside the Voltaic cell get used up. When the chemical reaction stops, the cell can no longer generate electricity and is considered dead.","keywords":["chemicals used up","reaction stops","no longer generate electricity"],"explanation":"Primary cells cannot regenerate their chemicals. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":27,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"In a scrapyard crane, why is the electromagnet switched OFF after moving scrap iron?","answer":"The electromagnet is switched OFF to stop the electric current, which causes the magnetic field to disappear. This releases the iron pieces exactly where they need to be dropped.","keywords":["switched OFF","magnetic field disappear","releases iron pieces"],"explanation":"Temporary magnetism allows for the easy release of heavy loads. Found on page 52.","page_number":"52"},
{"id":28,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"Why are electromagnets preferred over permanent magnets in cranes?","answer":"Electromagnets are preferred because their magnetism can be easily turned on and off by controlling the current, allowing the crane to pick up and release heavy loads instantly. Permanent magnets cannot release loads easily.","keywords":["turned on and off","controlling current","pick up and release"],"explanation":"Control over magnetism is crucial for material handling. Found on page 52.","page_number":"52"},
{"id":29,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":35},"question":"What is a fuse, and why is it used in electrical circuits?","answer":"A fuse is a safety device made of a thin wire with a low melting point. It melts and breaks the circuit when excess current flows, preventing appliances from overheating and catching fire.","keywords":["safety device","low melting point","breaks the circuit","preventing overheating"],"explanation":"Protects against overcurrent by utilizing the heating effect. Found on Chapter Notes page 5.","page_number":"5"},
{"id":30,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":35},"question":"Why do thin electric wires heat up faster than thick wires when the same current passes through them?","answer":"Thin wires offer more resistance to the flow of electric current compared to thick wires. Higher resistance results in a greater amount of electrical energy being converted into heat.","keywords":["more resistance","higher resistance","greater amount","converted into heat"],"explanation":"Resistance is inversely proportional to thickness. Found in Chapter Notes page 5.","page_number":"5"},
{"id":31,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"Two heating coils are connected to the same power source, but one produces more heat. What could be the reason?","answer":"The coil producing more heat likely has higher resistance. This could be because it is made of a different material, is thinner, or is longer than the other coil, causing greater heating effect.","keywords":["higher resistance","different material","thinner","longer"],"explanation":"Heat depends on material, length, and thickness. Found in Level 3 Worksheet.","page_number":"1"},
{"id":32,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"What happens if you connect an electromagnet to a battery of two cells instead of one?","answer":"Using two cells provides a larger electric current compared to a single cell. This creates a stronger magnetic field, meaning the electromagnet will attract more magnetic materials like iron clips.","keywords":["larger electric current","stronger magnetic field","attract more"],"explanation":"Current directly affects the strength of the electromagnet. Found on page 51.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":33,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":35},"question":"Why is it dangerous to touch electrical appliances with wet hands?","answer":"Water (especially tap water) contains ions that make it a good conductor of electricity. Touching appliances with wet hands reduces body resistance, potentially causing a severe electric shock.","keywords":["good conductor","reduces body resistance","electric shock"],"explanation":"Safety application of conductivity. Implied in general electrical safety context.","page_number":"2"},
{"id":34,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"How do we know if a cell or battery is dead?","answer":"A battery is considered dead when the chemical reactions inside it stop generating electric current. Devices connected to it, like a bulb or motor, will no longer function.","keywords":["chemical reactions stop","no longer function","stop generating current"],"explanation":"Exhaustion of chemicals means no electrical energy. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":35,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"If Sumana forgets to move the switch of her lifting electromagnet to OFF, what will eventually happen?","answer":"If left ON, the continuous flow of current will heat up the wire due to the heating effect, potentially draining the battery quickly and damaging the electromagnet coil through overheating.","keywords":["continuous flow","heat up","draining battery","overheating"],"explanation":" prolonged current causes heating and cell exhaustion. Found on page 60.","page_number":"60"},
{"id":36,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"Why are copper wires used for electrical transmission despite the heating effect?","answer":"Copper has very low electrical resistance. Because of this, it produces minimal heat when current flows through it, ensuring that electrical energy is efficiently transmitted without excessive energy loss.","keywords":["low electrical resistance","minimal heat","efficiently transmitted"],"explanation":"Low resistance prevents power loss during transmission. Found in Chapter Notes page 16.","page_number":"16"},
{"id":37,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":15,"max":35},"question":"What is a simple way to test if a lemon cell is producing electricity?","answer":"You can connect a small LED between the copper and zinc electrodes of the lemon cell. If the LED glows, it indicates that an electric current is flowing.","keywords":["connect LED","glows","current is flowing"],"explanation":"LED acts as a low-current indicator. Found on page 56.","page_number":"56"},
{"id":38,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":35},"question":"Mention two industrial applications of the heating effect of electric current.","answer":"In industries, the heating effect is used in high-temperature electric furnaces to melt and recycle scrap steel, and in large-scale heating equipment for processing materials.","keywords":["electric furnaces","melt and recycle","processing materials"],"explanation":"Beyond household use, it melts steel. Found on page 54.","page_number":"54"},
{"id":39,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":40},"question":"What role does the carbon rod play in a dry cell?","answer":"In a dry cell, the carbon rod is situated at the center, covered with a metal cap, and it functions as the positive electrode (terminal) for the electrical circuit.","keywords":["center","positive electrode","terminal"],"explanation":"It collects electrons from the external circuit. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":40,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":2,"expected_word_count":{"min":20,"max":35},"question":"Why must you ensure the LED is connected with correct polarity in a lemon cell experiment?","answer":"An LED only allows current to pass in one direction. The longer wire (positive) must connect to the positive terminal, and the shorter wire to the negative terminal to glow.","keywords":["one direction","longer wire positive","shorter wire negative"],"explanation":"LEDs are polarized components. Found on page 56.","page_number":"56"},
{"id":41,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Describe Oersted's experiment that proved the magnetic effect of electric current.","answer":"Oersted placed a magnetic compass near a wire. When he passed an electric current through the wire, he observed the compass needle deflect. When the current stopped, the needle returned to normal, proving that electric current generates a temporary magnetic field.","keywords":["magnetic compass","deflect","generates magnetic field"],"explanation":"Oersted's 1820 experiment established the link between electricity and magnetism. Found on page 48.","page_number":"48"},
{"id":42,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"How is an electromagnet constructed?","answer":"An electromagnet is constructed by taking a flexible insulated wire and wrapping it tightly in the form of a cylindrical coil around a soft iron core, like an iron nail. The ends of the wire are then connected to a battery to allow current to flow.","keywords":["insulated wire","cylindrical coil","soft iron core","connected to battery"],"explanation":"Construction requires a coil, core, and power source. Found on page 49.","page_number":"49"},
{"id":43,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"List three ways to increase the strength of an electromagnet.","answer":"The strength of an electromagnet can be increased by: 1) Increasing the number of turns of the wire in the coil. 2) Increasing the magnitude of the electric current (e.g., using more cells). 3) Using a soft iron core inside the coil.","keywords":["number of turns","magnitude of current","soft iron core"],"explanation":"Factors affecting magnetic strength. Found on page 51 and Slide 4.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":44,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Why does a current-carrying coil behave like a bar magnet? How can you determine its poles?","answer":"The current creates a magnetic field similar to a bar magnet. You can determine its poles by bringing a magnetic compass near its ends; the end that attracts the North pole of the compass is the South pole of the electromagnet, and vice versa.","keywords":["magnetic field","magnetic compass","North pole attracts South pole"],"explanation":"Electromagnets exhibit North and South poles just like permanent magnets. Found on page 51.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":45,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Explain the factors on which the heat generated in a wire depends.","answer":"The heat generated in a wire due to the heating effect depends on three main factors: the material of the wire (its resistance), the thickness and length of the wire, and the amount of current passing through it for a specific duration.","keywords":["material","resistance","thickness and length","duration"],"explanation":"Higher resistance, larger current, and longer time increase heat. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":46,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"What is a heating element? Name two appliances that use it.","answer":"A heating element is a rod or coil of high-resistance wire, usually nichrome, that becomes red hot and generates heat when electric current passes through it. Electric room heaters and electric irons are two common appliances that use heating elements.","keywords":["high-resistance wire","red hot","Electric room heaters","electric irons"],"explanation":"Heating elements are the core of thermal electrical appliances. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":47,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Give three differences between a dry cell and a Voltaic cell.","answer":"1) A dry cell uses a paste electrolyte, while a Voltaic cell uses a liquid electrolyte. 2) Dry cells are compact and highly portable, whereas Voltaic cells can leak and are less portable. 3) Dry cells are used in everyday devices like remotes, while Voltaic cells are mostly for demonstrations.","keywords":["paste electrolyte","liquid electrolyte","portable","demonstrations"],"explanation":"Comparison between wet and dry cell technologies. Found in Chapter Notes page 8.","page_number":"8"},
{"id":48,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"Describe the structure of a dry cell.","answer":"A dry cell consists of a zinc container that acts as the negative terminal. Inside, there is a carbon rod with a metal cap acting as the positive terminal. The carbon rod is surrounded by a thick, moist paste-like electrolyte containing manganese dioxide.","keywords":["zinc container","negative terminal","carbon rod positive","paste-like electrolyte"],"explanation":"Anatomy of standard dry cells. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":49,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"How do you make a simple Voltaic cell using a lemon?","answer":"To make a lemon cell, insert a copper strip and an iron nail (electrodes) into a juicy lemon, keeping them apart. The lemon juice acts as the electrolyte. Connecting wires to these metals will allow a small electric current to flow through a circuit.","keywords":["copper strip","iron nail","lemon juice electrolyte","current to flow"],"explanation":"Lemon juice is acidic and acts as an electrolyte with dissimilar metals. Found on page 56.","page_number":"56"},
{"id":50,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Why do we need safety devices in household circuits? Mention one such device.","answer":"Unwanted heating in wires due to high resistance or excessive current can cause energy loss, melt plastic plugs, and lead to severe electrical fires. A fuse is a safety device placed in circuits to melt and break the connection, preventing these incidents.","keywords":["unwanted heating","electrical fires","fuse","break the connection"],"explanation":"Safety devices manage the risks of the heating effect. Found on page 54.","page_number":"54"},
{"id":51,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"Why is recycling rechargeable batteries important for the environment?","answer":"Rechargeable batteries contain acids and valuable but toxic metals like lead, cadmium, and lithium. If thrown in regular garbage, they can cause fires or release harmful chemicals into the environment. Recycling prevents pollution and recovers valuable materials for reuse.","keywords":["toxic metals","harmful chemicals","Recycling prevents pollution"],"explanation":"E-waste management is crucial for sustainability. Found on page 61.","page_number":"61"},
{"id":52,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"How does the flow of electrons occur in a simple Voltaic cell?","answer":"In a Voltaic cell, the zinc electrode undergoes a chemical reaction and starts losing electrons, becoming negative. These electrons travel through the external wire to the copper electrode. This movement of electrons through the wire constitutes the electric current.","keywords":["zinc electrode","losing electrons","travel through wire","copper electrode"],"explanation":"Electron flow explains how chemical energy becomes electrical. Found in Chapter Notes page 6.","page_number":"6"},
{"id":53,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"An electromagnet used in a scrapyard suddenly stops lifting iron pieces even though the switch is ON. Give three possible reasons.","answer":"The electromagnet might fail if: 1) The battery is dead and no current is flowing. 2) The wire coil is broken, breaking the circuit. 3) The iron core has accidentally been removed, drastically weakening the magnetic field.","keywords":["battery dead","coil broken","iron core removed"],"explanation":"Troubleshooting a simple circuit. Found in Level 3 Worksheet page 1.","page_number":"1"},
{"id":54,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"Electric heating devices are often considered more convenient than traditional firewood. Give reasons considering societal impact.","answer":"Electric heaters are more convenient because they provide instant, easily controllable heat without producing harmful smoke, ash, or indoor air pollution. This improves respiratory health and eliminates the physical labor of gathering and burning firewood.","keywords":["instant controllable","no smoke","indoor air pollution","health"],"explanation":"Transition from biomass to electricity improves lifestyle and health. Found in Level 3 Worksheet page 14.","page_number":"14"},
{"id":55,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"What did Luigi Galvani discover, and how did Volta improve upon it to invent the battery?","answer":"Galvani noticed a frog's leg twitched when touched by two different metals, thinking electricity came from the frog. Volta proved the electricity came from the metals reacting with fluid, and used saltwater-soaked paper between metals to invent the first battery.","keywords":["frog's leg","metals reacting","saltwater-soaked paper","invent battery"],"explanation":"History of the battery's invention. Found on page 55.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":56,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"What is a solid-state battery and why is it considered the future?","answer":"A solid-state battery is a next-generation rechargeable battery that replaces liquid or paste electrolytes with solid materials. They are considered the future because they are much safer, charge faster, and last longer than current lithium-ion batteries.","keywords":["replaces liquid","solid materials","safer","charge faster"],"explanation":"Advancements in battery tech for sustainability. Found on page 58.","page_number":"58"},
{"id":57,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":35,"max":60},"question":"A student connects two cells instead of one to a coil during an experiment. How will this affect the electromagnet? Explain.","answer":"Connecting two cells increases the total voltage, which in turn increases the magnitude of the electric current flowing through the coil. A larger current creates a stronger magnetic field, meaning the electromagnet will become more powerful and attract more magnetic materials.","keywords":["increases current","stronger magnetic field","more powerful"],"explanation":"Current is directly proportional to magnetic field strength. Found on Level 2 Worksheet page 2 and textbook page 51.","page_number":"2"},
{"id":58,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":35,"max":60},"question":"Why do the wires of an electric heater become red hot while the connecting cord does not?","answer":"The heater wires are made of high-resistance nichrome, so passing current generates massive heat, making them red hot. The connecting cord is made of low-resistance copper, so the same current passes through it without producing significant heat.","keywords":["high-resistance nichrome","generates massive heat","low-resistance copper","without significant heat"],"explanation":"Comparing heating effects based on material resistance. Found on page 53 and Level 2 Worksheet.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":59,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":35,"max":60},"question":"Explain the working of an electric bell in relation to electromagnets.","answer":"An electric bell contains an electromagnet. When the switch is pressed, current flows and the electromagnet attracts a soft iron armature with a hammer attached, striking the bell. This movement breaks the circuit, the electromagnet loses its magnetism, and a spring pulls the armature back, repeating the cycle.","keywords":["attracts armature","striking bell","breaks circuit","repeating cycle"],"explanation":"Application of temporary magnetism. Found in Chapter Notes page 4.","page_number":"4"},
{"id":60,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"If you replace the iron nail in an electromagnet with a plastic pen, what will happen?","answer":"If the iron core is replaced with a plastic pen, the coil will still produce a weak magnetic field, but it will not be magnified because plastic is non-magnetic. The electromagnet will become extremely weak and likely fail to lift paper clips.","keywords":["weak magnetic field","not magnified","non-magnetic"],"explanation":"The role of the soft iron core is crucial for strength. Found on page 50.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":61,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"Why should an electric iron be left switched ON only when in use? What happens otherwise?","answer":"An electric iron converts electrical energy into heat continuously when ON. If left unattended, the heating element will continue to generate heat, which wastes electricity and poses a severe fire hazard as it can melt nearby objects or cause structural fires.","keywords":["converts continuous heat","wastes electricity","fire hazard"],"explanation":"Practical safety of heating devices. Found in Chapter Notes page 15.","page_number":"15"},
{"id":62,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":50},"question":"In an experiment, Neha slides the iron nail out of a current-carrying coil. Will the compass still deflect? Explain.","answer":"Yes, the compass will still deflect because a current-carrying coil itself generates a magnetic field. However, without the iron core, the magnetic field will be significantly weaker, so the deflection of the compass needle will be less than before.","keywords":["still deflect","coil generates field","significantly weaker"],"explanation":"The coil alone has a magnetic field, the core just amplifies it. Found on page 60.","page_number":"60"},
{"id":63,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":30,"max":55},"question":"Why do mobile phone batteries require charging more frequently after a year or two of use?","answer":"Mobile phones use rechargeable batteries like Lithium-ion. While they can be recharged and reused many times, they undergo chemical degradation over time. After repeated charging cycles, they slowly wear out and lose their capacity to hold a charge efficiently.","keywords":["rechargeable","chemical degradation","wear out","lose capacity"],"explanation":"Battery life cycles and degradation. Found on page 57.","page_number":"57"},
{"id":64,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"short_answer","marks":3,"expected_word_count":{"min":35,"max":60},"question":"A scrapyard magnet is weak and failing to lift loads. Suggest two technical solutions to fix this.","answer":"To increase the strength of the electromagnet, the scrapyard engineers can: 1) Increase the amount of electric current supplied to the coil by using a stronger power source. 2) Increase the number of turns of the wire wrapping around the iron core.","keywords":["Increase current","stronger power source","Increase number of turns"],"explanation":"Applying strength factors to a real-world scenario. Found in Chapter Notes page 14.","page_number":"14"},
{"id":65,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Explain in detail how a scrapyard crane uses an electromagnet to sort and move heavy iron pieces. Include what happens when the switch is turned ON and OFF.","answer":"A scrapyard crane uses a massive lifting electromagnet attached to its arm. It consists of a huge coil wrapped around an iron core. The crane operator moves the magnet over a pile of scrap. When the switch is turned ON, electric current flows, creating a powerful magnetic field that attracts heavy iron and steel objects. The crane then moves the attached load to the desired location. To release the scrap, the operator turns the switch OFF, stopping the current. The magnetic field instantly disappears, and the heavy iron pieces detach and fall safely into place.","keywords":["massive lifting electromagnet","current flows","creates powerful magnetic field","attracts heavy iron","switch OFF","magnetic field disappears"],"explanation":"Detailed working of an industrial electromagnet. Found on page 52.","page_number":"52"},
{"id":66,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Describe an experiment to demonstrate that a current-carrying wire behaves as a magnet.","answer":"Take a small magnetic compass and place it on a table. Stretch a straight piece of conducting wire over it. Connect the ends of the wire to a battery through a switch. Before switching it on, note the resting north-south direction of the compass. Move the switch to the ON position to allow electric current to flow. You will observe that the compass needle deflects from its original position. Now, switch it OFF; the needle returns to its original position. Since a compass only deflects near a magnet, this proves that the current-carrying wire generates a magnetic field around it.","keywords":["magnetic compass","conducting wire","switch ON","needle deflects","switch OFF","generates magnetic field"],"explanation":"Oersted's fundamental experiment description. Found on page 47-48.","page_number":"47"},
{"id":67,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Discuss the heating effect of electric current. Mention its cause, the factors it depends on, and three daily life applications.","answer":"When electric current flows through a conductor, it faces opposition called resistance. This electrical friction converts some electrical energy into heat energy, causing the wire to warm up; this is the heating effect. The amount of heat generated depends on the material's resistance, the thickness and length of the wire, and the duration and magnitude of the current. Daily life applications include electric irons, room heaters, and water heating immersion rods, which all use high-resistance nichrome coils (heating elements) to purposefully generate high amounts of heat for household tasks.","keywords":["faces opposition","resistance","converts electrical energy","heat generated depends","material thickness length","electric irons heaters"],"explanation":"Comprehensive overview of the heating effect. Found on page 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":68,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Explain the construction, working, and chemical process inside a simple Voltaic cell.","answer":"A simple Voltaic (or Galvanic) cell is constructed using two metal rods made of different materials, typically zinc and copper, which act as electrodes. These are partially dipped into an electrolyte, which is usually a weak acid or salt solution in a glass container. Chemically, the zinc rod starts losing electrons, becoming negative, while the copper rod becomes positive. When connected by an external wire, these electrons flow from the zinc to the copper, generating an electric current that can light a small lamp. Bubbles of hydrogen gas form at the copper rod as the reaction continues. Over time, the chemicals are consumed, and the cell goes dead.","keywords":["zinc and copper","electrodes","electrolyte","losing electrons","flow zinc to copper","generating electric current"],"explanation":"Detailed working of the primary liquid cell. Found on page 55 and Chapter Notes page 6.","page_number":"55"},
{"id":69,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Compare dry cells and voltaic cells in detail across five different aspects.","answer":"1. Electrolyte: Dry cells use a thick moist chemical paste, whereas voltaic cells use a liquid acid/salt solution. 2. Portability: Because dry cells lack free-flowing liquid, they do not leak easily and are highly portable; voltaic cells can spill and are largely stationary. 3. Structure: Dry cells are compact and sealed in a zinc container, while voltaic cells are open glass containers with dipped rods. 4. Electrodes: Dry cells use a zinc container (negative) and a carbon rod (positive); voltaic typically uses zinc and copper rods. 5. Usage: Dry cells are standard for consumer electronics like remotes and toys, whereas simple voltaic cells are mostly used for laboratory demonstrations.","keywords":["paste vs liquid","highly portable","sealed zinc container","carbon rod","consumer electronics"],"explanation":"Full comparison from the chapter notes. Found on Chapter Notes page 8.","page_number":"8"},
{"id":70,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Design an activity to compare the heating effect of different wire thicknesses. What will be the observation and conclusion?","answer":"Activity: Take two thin nichrome wires of equal length but different thicknesses (e.g., 0.3 mm and 0.6 mm). Set up a circuit with a cell and a switch. Connect the thinner wire first, turn the switch ON for 30 seconds, then switch OFF and carefully feel the warmth. Repeat the exact same procedure with the thicker wire. \nObservation: The thinner wire will feel significantly hotter than the thicker wire. \nConclusion: The heating effect depends on the thickness of the wire. Thinner wires offer higher electrical resistance compared to thicker ones, meaning they convert more electrical energy into heat energy when the same current flows through them.","keywords":["different thicknesses","circuit with cell","thinner wire hotter","heating effect depends","higher electrical resistance"],"explanation":"Experimental design for heating effect variables. Found on page 61.","page_number":"61"},
{"id":71,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"How do safety devices utilize the heating effect of electric current? Explain the role of a fuse and why selecting the right rating is important.","answer":"Safety devices like fuses purposefully use the heating effect to protect household circuits. A fuse consists of a special thin wire with a specific, low melting point. Under normal conditions, current flows safely. However, if a short circuit or overload occurs, the excessive current rapidly increases the heat generated in the fuse wire. The wire melts and breaks the circuit, instantly stopping the current flow before appliances overheat or catch fire. It is vital to use appropriately rated fuses (matching the specified electric current of the connection) because if a high-rating fuse is used for a low-power circuit, it won't melt in time, failing to prevent a fire.","keywords":["protect household circuits","low melting point","excessive current rapidly increases","wire melts breaks circuit","appropriately rated fuses"],"explanation":"Mechanism and importance of fuses. Found on page 54 and Chapter Notes page 5.","page_number":"54"},
{"id":72,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"A student wants to make a strong electromagnet for a science fair. Explain the step-by-step construction and the scientific principles behind making it as strong as possible.","answer":"To build a strong electromagnet, the student should first select a soft iron nail to act as the core, as iron concentrates magnetic field lines. Next, they must take a long, flexible, insulated copper wire and tightly wind it around the nail to form a cylindrical coil. The more turns they wrap, the stronger the magnetic field will become. The ends of the wire should be connected to a battery pack. Instead of a single cell, using a battery of 2 or 3 cells will push a larger electric current through the wire, significantly amplifying the strength. When the circuit is closed, the combined effect of the iron core, high number of turns, and strong current will create a very powerful temporary magnet.","keywords":["soft iron nail core","tightly wind","more turns","battery of cells","larger electric current","powerful temporary magnet"],"explanation":"Synthesis of electromagnet construction and strength factors. Found on page 49-51.","page_number":"49"},
{"id":73,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Discuss the environmental impact of batteries. Why is the shift towards rechargeable and solid-state batteries considered vital for sustainability?","answer":"Standard single-use dry cells create immense waste because they are discarded once dead. Batteries contain toxic heavy metals (lead, cadmium, lithium) and acids. Improper disposal in regular garbage leads to soil and water pollution and fire risks. Rechargeable batteries (like Lithium-ion) are vital for sustainability because they can be recharged by reversing their chemical reactions, allowing them to be reused hundreds of times, thereby drastically reducing the volume of e-waste. Furthermore, scientists are developing solid-state batteries that replace flammable liquid electrolytes with solid materials, making them much safer, more efficient, and longer-lasting, aligning with the global need for environmentally friendly electrical power sources.","keywords":["toxic heavy metals","pollution and fire","reversing chemical reactions","drastically reducing e-waste","solid-state batteries safer"],"explanation":"Environmental context of batteries and future tech. Found on page 58 and 61.","page_number":"58"},
{"id":74,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":50,"max":90},"question":"We have four similar coils made of iron, copper, aluminium, and nichrome. If connected to identical circuits, which one will produce the most heat and why?","answer":"The nichrome coil will produce the most heat. This happens because the heating effect of electric current depends heavily on the resistance of the material. Out of iron, copper, aluminium, and nichrome, nichrome has the highest electrical resistance. It strongly opposes the flow of electric current, causing a large portion of the electrical energy to be converted into heat energy. In contrast, copper and aluminium are excellent conductors with very low resistance, so they will generate minimal heat.","keywords":["nichrome coil","highest electrical resistance","opposes flow","converted into heat","minimal heat"],"explanation":"Material property application from textbook activity. Found on page 60 and 53.","page_number":"53"},
{"id":75,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Explain the phenomenon of the Earth behaving like a giant magnet and its importance to life and navigation.","answer":"The Earth itself behaves like a giant magnet due to activities deep inside its core. The movement of liquid iron in the Earth's outer core creates massive electric currents, which in turn generate a vast global magnetic field through the magnetic effect of current. This magnetic field is incredibly important for life. Firstly, many migratory birds, fish, and animals possess a natural ability to sense this field, using it to navigate accurately across entire continents and oceans. Secondly, the Earth's magnetic field acts as a protective planetary shield, deflecting and blocking harmful, high-energy particles coming from space and the sun, thus protecting life on the surface.","keywords":["liquid iron","outer core","massive electric currents","navigate accurately","planetary shield","blocking harmful particles"],"explanation":"Earth's magnetism origin and benefits. Found on page 51.","page_number":"51"},
{"id":76,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Describe an experiment to make an electric cell using a fruit, testing it, and understanding polarity.","answer":"Take 5 to 6 juicy lemons. In each lemon, insert a copper wire and an iron nail a short distance apart. Connect the iron nail of the first lemon to the copper wire of the second lemon using connecting wires, creating a series battery. Take a small LED and connect its longer wire (positive terminal) to the copper wire of the first lemon, and its shorter wire (negative terminal) to the iron nail of the last lemon. The acidic lemon juice acts as the electrolyte, allowing chemical reactions with the metals to generate current. The glowing LED confirms electricity. If the LED doesn't glow, reversing the connections fixes it, demonstrating strict polarity requirements.","keywords":["juicy lemons","copper wire iron nail","series battery","LED longer wire","electrolyte","glowing LED"],"explanation":"Fruit battery experiment detailing polarity and electrolytes. Found on page 56.","page_number":"56"},
{"id":77,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Explain the difference between conventional current flow and electron flow using the working of a Voltaic cell.","answer":"In a Voltaic cell containing zinc and copper electrodes in an electrolyte, chemical reactions cause the zinc rod to lose electrons, making it the negative terminal. The copper rod becomes the positive terminal. Inside the wires of the external circuit, the actual physical particles moving are the negatively charged electrons, which flow from the negative zinc to the positive copper. However, historically, electricity was thought to be a flow of positive charge. Therefore, the direction of conventional electric current is defined as flowing in the opposite direction: from the positive terminal (copper) to the negative terminal (zinc) through the external circuit. Both concepts describe the same phenomenon but in reverse directions.","keywords":["lose electrons","zinc negative","copper positive","electrons flow zinc to copper","conventional current","positive to negative"],"explanation":"Details the difference between electron flow and conventional current in a primary cell. Found in Chapter Notes page 7.","page_number":"7"},
{"id":78,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"A student creates a circuit with a coil but no core, observing very weak magnetism. Detail three specific changes they can make to lift heavy iron objects, explaining the reason for each.","answer":"To upgrade the weak coil into a powerful lifting electromagnet, the student must make three changes. First, insert a soft iron core (like a thick nail) inside the coil; the iron concentrates the magnetic field, acting as a multiplier for the strength. Second, increase the number of turns in the wire coil; each additional loop adds to the total magnetic field, compounding the pulling force. Third, increase the current by adding more electric cells to the battery in series; a higher magnitude of electric current directly generates a proportionally stronger magnetic field. Implementing all three will allow the magnet to lift heavy iron.","keywords":["soft iron core","concentrates magnetic field","increase number of turns","adds to total field","increase current","proportionally stronger"],"explanation":"Practical engineering application of electromagnet strength factors. Found on page 50-51.","page_number":"50"},
{"id":79,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":60,"max":100},"question":"Why are electromagnets essential in electric bells? Trace the sequence of events from when the button is pressed to when the bell rings and resets.","answer":"Electromagnets are essential in electric bells because they provide the necessary temporary, rapid ON-OFF magnetic action. When the user presses the button, the circuit is completed, and current flows through the electromagnet's coil. The coil becomes magnetized and attracts a soft iron armature. As the armature moves toward the magnet, the hammer attached to it strikes the metal gong, ringing the bell. However, this forward movement pulls the contact point away from a screw, breaking the electrical circuit. The current stops, the electromagnet instantly loses its magnetism, and a spring pulls the armature back to its original position. This re-establishes contact, completing the circuit again, and the cycle repeats rapidly.","keywords":["temporary rapid ON-OFF","current flows","attracts armature","strikes gong","breaking circuit","loses magnetism spring pulls"],"explanation":"Complete mechanical and electrical working of a bell. Found in Chapter Notes page 4.","page_number":"4"},
{"id":80,"subject":"Science","chapter":"Electricity: Magnetic and Heating Effects-QA-v1","difficulty":"hard","question_type":"long_answer","marks":5,"expected_word_count":{"min":50,"max":100},"question":"Analyze how the heating effect of electric current is related to the concept of energy conversion, providing examples of both useful and harmful energy conversions.","answer":"The heating effect of electric current is a direct example of energy conversion, specifically electrical energy turning into heat (thermal) energy due to the resistance of a conductor. When this conversion is intentional, it is highly useful; for example, nichrome wires in electric room heaters, kettles, and electric irons convert electricity to heat to warm rooms, boil water, or press clothes. However, when unintentional, this conversion is harmful. For instance, ordinary copper transmission wires and household switchboards can overheat if too much current flows. This results in energy loss, melting of plastic insulation, and dangerous electrical fires, necessitating safety devices like fuses to stop the flow.","keywords":["energy conversion","electrical into heat","useful conversion heaters","harmful conversion","overheat energy loss fires"],"explanation":"Synthesizes the dual nature (useful/harmful) of resistance and heating. Found on page 53-54.","page_number":"54"}
]
